To compute $\binom{13}{4} + \binom{13}{9}$, we can use the following combinatorial argument:

Imagine you have 13 distinct objects.  We want to count the number of ways to choose a group of 4 objects from these 13, plus the number of ways to choose a group of 9 objects.

Notice that these two scenarios are complementary.  Every possible group of 4 objects is either included in a group of 9 or not.  Therefore, the total number of ways to choose a group of 4 or 9 objects is equal to the total number of ways to choose any group of objects from the 13.

This means:

$$\binom{13}{4} + \binom{13}{9} = \binom{13}{4} + \binom{13}{13 - 4} = \binom{13}{4} + \binom{13}{9} = \binom{14}{5}$$

Now we can calculate:

$$\binom{14}{5} = \dfrac{14!}{5!9!} = \dfrac{14 \times 13 \times 12 \times 11 \times 10}{5 \times 4 \times 3 \times 2 \times 1} = 2002$$



\begin{equation*}
\boxed{2002}
\end{equation*}

