Let's tackle this determinant problem.  We can simplify it using the change-of-base formula for logarithms: $\log_a b = \frac{\log b}{\log a}$.

Substituting this into our determinant, we get:

\begin{align*}
\begin{vmatrix} 1 & \frac{\log y}{\log x} & \frac{\log z}{\log x} \\ \frac{\log x}{\log y} & 1 & \frac{\log z}{\log y} \\ \frac{\log x}{\log z} & \frac{\log y}{\log z} & 1 \end{vmatrix} 
\end{align*}

Now, let's expand this determinant along the first row:

\begin{align*}
&= 1 \begin{vmatrix} 1 & \frac{\log z}{\log y} \\ \frac{\log y}{\log z} & 1 \end{vmatrix} - \frac{\log y}{\log x} \begin{vmatrix} \frac{\log x}{\log y} & \frac{\log z}{\log y} \\ \frac{\log x}{\log z} & 1 \end{vmatrix} + \frac{\log z}{\log x} \begin{vmatrix} \frac{\log x}{\log y} & 1 \\ \frac{\log x}{\log z} & \frac{\log y}{\log z} \end{vmatrix} \\
&= 1 \left( 1 - \frac{\log z}{\log y} \cdot \frac{\log y}{\log z} \right) - \frac{\log y}{\log x} \left( \frac{\log x}{\log y} - \frac{\log z}{\log y} \cdot \frac{\log x}{\log z} \right) + \frac{\log z}{\log x} \left( \frac{\log x}{\log y} \cdot \frac{\log y}{\log z} - 1 \right) \\
&= 1 - 1 - \frac{\log y}{\log x} \left( 1 - 1 \right) + \frac{\log z}{\log x} \left( 1 - 1 \right) \\
&= \boxed{1}
\end{align*}

